Did you know we had another store “ELDER AND PINE” 2013-2015 it was Vintage + hand selected new brands like polar, Kennedy, juniper ridge, Stanley etc. we specialized in rare vintage t shirts, denim and workwear. My husband Nick ran the shop and did the buying and ordering for it. It was in the neighborhood we lived in on 40th/Webster in Oakland. At a time when Sub Rosa coffee, 1234 go records, marquee salon, manifesto bicycles and homeroom Mac and cheese were the only businesses in the neighborhood. It was an exciting time to try something new and rents hadn’t skyrocketed yet. We had pop ups and events including a motorcycle rally that you had to see to believe. We were even in an American Express commercial. After a few years we decided to move the shop into our second floor of Pretty Penny in Rockridge Oakland. It was a money saver and we had the space to merge. If you have followed us for a long time you have seen that we have taken risks and sometimes they work and sometimes they don’t. But no matter what we always learn something and tried. We are less into risk taking these days and look for stability and consistency. That comes with age and running small businesses with its many pivots for almost 17 years.

We have had 7 store fronts/business spaces over the last 17 years. They have housed Pretty Penny Clothing, Elder & Pine, Watermelon Sugar Salon, Guerrero Hair Studio And Hey Pretty Hair Studio. 1. 2006 Pretty Penny opened on milvia/university in Berkeley California 2. College avenue rockridge Oakland California 3. San Francisco 24th/Guerrero 4. Temescal 40th/Webster 5. Warehouse space in Bellingham Washington 6. Store Front Elm Street Bellingham Washington 7. CURRENT - college avenue elmwood Berkeley California - my experience in being a small business owner has meant trying new things and pivoting. Sometimes they have worked and sometimes they haven’t. Successes and loss has felt like a wave over these last 17 years with so many valuable and important life lessons along the way. With the introduction of online selling/online business the store fronts run in tandem with a full time online store so it’s double work/2 businesses always running at the same time and in between. The online store has never stopped during transitions and Covid. I have run the online out of my home studio many times during transition. Thank you for being a part of our journey.

Being a small business owner and a mother. I went into labor with my daughter while working at the rockridge Oakland store. It was September 19th 2011 and i wasn’t supposed to be due until September 28th. She was 8 days early and I ended up having my daughter Vienna at 427 am the next morning of September 20th. Being a new mom and navigating a small business was a juggling act because at that time my husband had his hair salon “Watermelon Sugar Salon” in San Francisco And I had Pretty Penny. We were really lucky to have great staff support and a community of friends to rally around us. Because we worked for ourselves we didn’t have maternity leave and had to go back to work quickly taking turns staying home with our daughter and bringing her to work. I remember my husband doing a haircut with her strapped to him. Our daughter has since experienced being the child of small business owners roller coaster. Growing up along side our employees and customers. Hearing about the businesses everyday of her life. Meeting and saying goodbye to staff as they moved on. Sometimes I wish I could have shielded her from the very low times we’ve experienced as a business but I know there are lessons everywhere for her as long as we communicate them well and help her understand why things happen. I am grateful that we have gotten to spend so much time with her because we made our own schedules and have been our own bosses. Vienna has always had a space in the stores to hang out. In Bellingham nick built a check out counter with a open back so she had a little hang out spot inside the counter. She currently has a work space in the back with a computer so she can do homework and art. If you’ve been by the new shop you’ve probably seen her. She is going into middle school ( 6th grade ) next year and I am so proud of the person she’s growing up to be. She is a huge part of Pretty Penny and our stores community. Everything I do and my drive to succeed, keep persisting and trying is because of her. #mom #smallbusinessowner #family #persistence #community #17yearanniversay #wearemorethanashopweareacommunity #prettypenny #prettypennyclothing #heypretty #cutecustomeralert #mom #moms

We support OUSD ( Oakland Unified School District) teachers strike that has started today. “The district is proposing that every teacher get a raise in the range of at least 13% to as much as 22 percent. Raises will also be provided for the district's nurses, counselors and psychologists”. The teachers' union says the negotiations are focused on more than just money. They want smaller class sizes, counselors at every school and better classroom conditions with air filtration and climate control. According to the California Deptartment of Education, the average starting salary for a teacher in the state is just over $51,000 a year. In Oakland, which has a higher cost of living compared to the state average. Oakland Housing Market Trends
What is the housing market like in Oakland today?
In March 2023, Oakland home prices were up 1.8% compared to last year, selling for a median price of $910K. As of April 2023, the average rent for a 1-bedroom apartment in Oakland, CA is $2,150. This is a 7% increase compared to the previous year. 
Inflation, cost of living and funding makes this place a very difficult place to live. BIG PICTURE - How can an average worker live in Oakland? How can our OUSD teachers and school district workers afford to live here without a significant pay raise and support? 
How much has homelessness increased in the Bay Area?
with a significant share of the population concentrated in the Bay Area. On any given night, 38,000 individuals in the Bay Area are homeless, an increase of 35 percent since 2019. Point-in-time (PIT) counts for Bay Area counties in 2022. This is a very challenging place to live with huge income inequality and access. These are huge issues in Oakland and our teachers, school administrators, counselors and school district workers deserve better. Oakland kids deserve better. #ousd #ousdstrike #accessibility #inflation #wealthandprivilege #tech #gentrification #isupportunions #strike #workersrights #teachersdeservebetter #access

SWIPE RIGHT TO SEE MORE. I haven’t done many creative styling photo shoots since before the pandemic and I miss it. I miss the creativity and energy of Hair, makeup a photographer and models. I miss building a set, finding the right lighting and choosing locations. I’ve been in small business survival mode for 4 years now and to be completely honest I feel I’m crawling out of a dark place of loss and motivation to create. Im sure most of us are questioning what in the hell am I doing, where has the time gone or we are changing our minds about how we spend our time, work and be creative or how do we create ? I want to add this element of pure joy and creativity back into my business and my life to share with you. If you are a creative who has energetic self expression and want to collaborate on photoshoots DM me

SWIPE RIGHT - Months ago we bought from the estate of two beautiful sisters late mother who had one of the most historical Bay Area based legacies collections with connections to I Magnin and Helga Howie to name a few. We heard stories about their mother and got back stories on the vintage pieces we bought. I was able to relay these stories to the people who bought these items online and in the store, it felt like a beautiful tribute to their mother. • We were so excited to get a surprise visit yesterday and our kiddo received a beautiful vintage I magnin picture frame that was made in Italy and a card that said “you are loved” this is just one example of all the lifelong connections I’ve made with people through my business. SOLD.  ABOUT THE DESIGNER: 

Eskolin-Nurmesniemi studied ceramics at the Institute of Industrial Arts (in Finnish: Taideteollinen oppilaitos) in Helsinki, Finland. After graduating, she designed glassware and ceramics for Arabia and Nuutajärvi. In 1957, she received a gold medal at the Milan Triennial XI for her glassware.[1]

Eskolin-Nurmesniemi joined the Finnish company Marimekko in 1953. She designed patterns for many of their printed fabrics in the 1950s; together with Maija Isola, she was responsible for most of Marimekko's patterns.[2][3] Nurmesniemi's signature product was a simply striped red and white shirt named Jokapoika, in 1956; she went on to create a large number of striking designs.[4]

Nurmesniemi left Marimekko in 1960 due to conflicts with Marimekko founder Armi Ratia.[5] She founded her own company, Vuokko Oy, in 1964, and designed textiles as well as ready-to-wear clothing and accessories.[1] This company closed its doors in 1988. In 1990 Nurmesniemi founded a second company, Vuokko Nurmesniemi Oy.[6] SOLD

During the pandemic lockdown we were struggling to find a way to connect to people. We wanted to do something safe for the people in our community and give them something to do outside of their homes. We came up with the idea to have an art show with our 3 display window panels. I did a window with all my old concert tickets, flyers and magazine cut outs. My daughters ( she was 8 at the time ) window was a hand painted piece of her art that expressed unity. My husband did a window with his hand painted designs on clothing. We put a speaker with music on outside and used bright pink tape to create 6 feet distance markers on the ground. As people came by we waved through the window and exchanged smiles. It was amazing and added some light during a very dark and uncertain time. I have been doing a lot of reflecting lately about having a brick and mortar small business and how they contribute to communities and what the ramifications are of losing so many due to the massive amounts of closures over the last 4 years. I wonder what it will it take to keep them open, running and thriving in 2023. What does the long term loss look like to communities with empty store fronts, no doors open to walk into for a quick chat and to physically touch items, try things on and experience a real life connection. This topic entangles the internet and online shopping, convenience and a new normal that isn’t going anywhere. Now what ?

Owning a small business is vulnerable and personal, it’s what makes it beautiful and special. I’ve learned this over the last 17 years owning Pretty Penny. So I am choosing to share what’s going on instead of have people wonder  why the stores hours change, or we might close early or whatever our plan is for the future (we are working on it ) I have been going through a health crisis since September and it’s ramping up and has become a medical emergency and I am waiting for a surgery date that should be next week. This surgery will leave me out of the shop and in recovery for 3-6 weeks. My husband nick @stmarydoeshair has been holding things down for me in the store since Wednesday while taking care of me, our child, working with his clients, being in school and doing an internship for @kpfaradio if you are in this shop today or Sunday and he’s upstairs doing hair while trying to watch the sales floor please be patient and understanding. We are doing our best to keep our business open while trying to scramble to put together a plan. As small business owners and most working class people in the US our lives are a delicate house of cards where if 1 thing goes wrong or 1 medical emergency it can all fall apart. Like most small business owners we work our businesses full time plus many of us like me work solo. I haven’t always but in 2023 that’s the way it’s had to be. I do all the buying, work on the sales floor the 5 days a week we are open and work the online store, without me working there is no Pretty Penny + no income. Please be patient while we try to figure out what to do and come up with a plan. This is as far out as we can plan right now Nick is at the shop 12-6 today and Sunday 12-5 he will be with his hair clients and watching the shop, please be kind and patient. It’s complicated and there’s so much more but this is all I’m willing to share for now. The online has over 400 products to SHOP. I will do my best and try to add more in store and online before my surgery. Thank you for all your support through the years, it means so much xo Sarah

Hi all! The last few months have been a struggle for my family. Sarah has gone in to surgery this morning to repair a gynecological issue that finally reached a critical max for her. It had gotten to a place where it was impacting her daily life and this was the only solution to get Sarah back in better health. On top of this our daughter Vienna broke her finger back in September and when Kaiser screwed up with the first cast and placement of her finger she then needed to have reconstructive surgery, two pins and another cast. She is working on regaining full mobility in her finger in PT. Sarahs sister Rebekah started a go fund me for them to help us with the medical expenses and loss of work for us. Follow the link in the bio if you can help out and please share as well. Thank you all for your support and love. 
Nick, Sarah and Vienna

UPDATE: I am half way through my recovery. I haven’t been able to be in the shop, except this Monday to take some photos and video and ended up hurting myself which put me on bed rest for a few days so I am back to rest and recovery and not going to push it. I miss you guys and I miss the shop. If all is well I will be back in the shop February 4th. Viennas ( our daughter ) is good and recovering from her finger surgery and is in PT. Zena helped us out last month and Nick @stmarydoeshair has been holding down the store while seeing his clients, cooking, cleaning, childcare, school and an internship. I am so grateful for him and his care. Thank you @shopbasalt for keeping the store stocked with gorgeous vintage. I am also so grateful for you and all your support, it has meant so much. If you want to read more about what’s been going on there is a link in our bio. Happy New Year I appreciate you ❤️ #wearemorethanashopweareacommunity
